# Teaching Strategies > Learning New Tools

Scratch is a block based visual programming language developed by MIT.  In Scratch you can program animations, games, music, simulations and interactive stories.

Watch this video to get a quick introduction to Scratch:

<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/uq8jYUmUCr4" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>

We'll explore Scratch throughout this online PD, and give you plenty of time to practice, so don't worry! We'll also provide you with lots of Scratch support resources, but here are a few you might want to bookmark now, just in case:

- PDF Tutorial: [Getting Started in Scratch](https://cdn.scratch.mit.edu/scratchr2/static/ __4eb10d5d92e10491ab6572c8f8482bbf__ /pdfs/help/Getting-Started-Guide-Scratch2.pdf)
- More Videos: [https://scratch.mit.edu/help/videos/#](https://scratch.mit.edu/help/videos/#)
- Even More Videos: [http://learnscratch.org/video-courses](http://learnscratch.org/video-courses)
- Scratch Educator Page: [http://scratched.gse.harvard.edu/](http://scratched.gse.harvard.edu/)
- Scratch Discussion Forum: [http://scratched.gse.harvard.edu/discussions](http://scratched.gse.harvard.edu/discussions)
- Projects in Scratch: [https://scratch.mit.edu/projects/54669314/](https://scratch.mit.edu/projects/54669314/) and
[https://scratch.mit.edu/projects/83495694/](https://scratch.mit.edu/projects/83495694/)

We hope you have fun with Scratch. We know your students will!

